Today, there are around 20,000 consultants operating in the UK. Word on the grapevine suggests the younger, less experienced consultant is now less in demand: the client is unwilling to pay for \ldblquote bag-carriers\rdblquote 
. Consultants 35-40 years old wi
th 6-7 years experience in consultancy seem able to command higher prices. Smaller consultancies have started to encroach on the market previously dominated by a few large firms, many of which appear to have moved backwards. (See Management Consultancy, J
une 1992).
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\f22\fs22 
\par }{\b\f22\fs22 Why? What forces could now be determining your competitive success in this increasingly crowded market place?}{\f22\fs22  Clearly many consultant qualities can help to create success and we will in this article focus on a particular one: 
\ldblquote authenticity\rdblquote . We 
believe (based upon our experience in providing intensive consultancy skills training for over 800 people in the last seven years) that some consultancies, in particular the large firms, could now need to make some important changes to arrest their declin
e. These fall into two categories:
\par }{\f22\fs8 -\tab }{\f22\fs22 working authentically with your client
\par }{\f22\fs8 -\tab }{\f22\fs22 managing consultants authentically.
\par 
\par \ldblquote Interesting, but what has \lquote being authentic\rquote  got to do with it?\rdblquote , we can hear you ask. \ldblquote Surely\rdblquote , you may be saying to yourself, \ldblquote \lquote being real\rquote  
could interfere with the power play that is the essence of good business.\rdblquote  We disagree: the consultancy transaction is different from a normal business deal.
\par 
\par As a consultant you are better advised to model yourself upon a doctor or a lawyer where professi
onalism and trust often overrule self-interest rather than say a used car salesman. Consultants often undermine their own success with their client by driving down the most obvious route towards the deal and faking not just their experience but also (and 
more importantly in our view) their feelings and reactions when face to face with the client. Some large firms encourage and require their consultants to fake in order to survive, for example, in answer to the question \ldblquote 
how do you feel about this project?\rdblquote . }{\b\f22\fs22 We believe that \ldblquote authenticity\rdblquote  or \ldblquote being real\rdblquote 
 is potentially an important differentiator, available to the experienced consultant by virtue of their experience but denied to them by the corporate structures within which many of them operate.
\par }{\f22\fs22 
\par If you read on you will find out why we think so. Specifically, we will explain what being \ldblquote authentic\rdblquote  means, why \ldblquote authentic\rdblquote 
 consultants can be relatively more successful in this climate, how you could manage consultants to gain the benefits of authenticity. We inte
nd the thoughts presented to be provocative in places and we accept that they may not be true of every client, consultant or consultancy firm.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj\keepn\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\fs22\lang2057 {\f22 The client\rquote s reality
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\f22\fs22 We are not the first people to coin the term \ldblquote authenticity\rdblquote  in relation to consultancy skil
ls (see Peter Block, Flawless Consulting, Pfeiffer & Co., 1981). However, we do argue for its particular relevance in today\rquote s climate. Let us illustrate this with an example.
\par 
\par All consultancy starts with a client. So how might the client be feeling in today\rquote 
s business environment? A recent TV advertisement for Mercury Communications makes the point very well. A middle manager is being interrogated by two stony-faced executives, 
being asked to justify what value he has added to the business in the last 12 months. We all squirm in our seats as we watch the panic stricken middle manager turn the situation around (with a little help from Mercury of course!).
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s30\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs22\lang2057 {\f22 Perhaps he has seen resp
ected colleagues go in the last round of cuts. His job alternatives are limited. Confidence and self-esteem have been shaken badly by the number of recession-hit plans and unfulfilled strategies. He may not know how near the top of the boss\rquote 
s hit list he has reached (and there may not be many people left above him). There are no longer any hiding places.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\f22\fs22 
\par A high degree of accountability is now commonplace and exists at almost all levels and in all parts of the recession-hit corporation. It operates whether 
the client is junior or more senior, from a line or staff function, below the board or on it. Even the Chief Executive feels accountable to shareholders, customers and employees. Pay your way, justify your existence (as in the Mercury example) or expect t
o go.
\par 
\par Winning new business against this background requires either a lot of luck, or more likely a client who knows and trusts the consultant totally. Trust can arise from previous successful work together. }{\b\f22\fs22 
In a new relationship, trust arises most quickly from a set of behaviours we describe as \ldblquote being authentic\rdblquote . \ldblquote Faking\rdblquote  is the opposite of \ldblquote authentic\rdblquote 
, it is easily detected by most clients, it smells rotten and ensures consultant failure.
\par }{\f22 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj\keepn\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\fs22\lang2057 {\f22 Being real with the client
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\f22\fs22 We follow a definition of consultancy as \ldblquote helping the client to solve problems }{\i\f22\fs22 at their request\rdblquote . }{\f22\fs22 
The early meetings with a client consist of learning about the problems, building up confidence and trust in one another and gaining }{\i\f22\fs22 permission }{\f22\fs22 to work }{\i\f22\fs22 with }{\f22\fs22 the client to solve the problems.
\par 
\par We all know it\rquote s harder than it used to be. Permission is less easily obtained from a
\par vulnerable, recession-worn client and more senior level people need to give their permission
\par before you have authority to proceed. See Box 1.
\par 
\par }\pard \qj\nowidctlpar\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \brdrl\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp80 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \brdrr\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp80 \adjustright {\f22\fs22 BOX 1: NON-AUTHENTIC EXAMPLES
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s32\qj\nowidctlpar\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \brdrl\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp80 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \brdrr\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp80 \adjustright \i\fs22\lang2057 {\f22 Scenario 1: The \ldblquote smart ass, non-authentic\rdblquote 
 consultant walks into your office, introduces him or herself, claims some incredible experience, presents themselves as a super-being from another planet, pushes out some \ldblquote new\rdblquote  ideas, makes some wild promises, presu
mes you are interested in commissioning some work, promises it is easy.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \brdrl\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp80 \brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \brdrr\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp80 \adjustright \lang2057 {\i\f22\fs22 
\par Scenario 2: The \ldblquote sympathetic, non-authentic\rdblquote  consultant walks into your office, makes eye contact, asks you lots of questions, listens carefully, summarises what you have told them, g
oes painstakingly through all the steps they have been taught on the basic consultancy skills course they have just attended, pinpoints a problem and asks if}{\i\f22\fs28  }{\i\f22\fs22 you would like them to write a proposal.
\par 
\par If you were the client how might you react to these approaches?
\par }\pard \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\f22\fs22 
\par Consultants will easily dismiss their lack of success with new clients as down to \ldblquote the wrong chemistry\rdblquote 
. This can let them off the hook too easily. In reality they mishandled themselves in these situations. The scenarios in box 1 were non-authenti
c approaches which waste both client and consultant time and are doomed to failure. The dialogue the consultants initiated with the client was not real and was disconnected from the client\rquote s world.
\par 
\par So what can the consultants do to help themselves in this situation? Perhaps it is easier to start with how NOT to do it. See Box 2.
